  1. Use the set-up of exercise 6. Drop unused factor levels in cntry, and make a design matrix like I did in my slides (i.e., keep only imwbcnt, rlgblg, rlgdgr, rlgatnd, pray, cntry, par_edu, gndr, pspwght, and apply casewise deletion). That design matrix has observations left.
ESS <- ESS %>%
  mutate(
    cntry = fct_drop(cntry)
  ) %>%
  select(imwbcnt, rlgdgr, rlgatnd, eduyrs, par_edu, cntry, gndr, pspwght) %>%
  drop_na()
  1. Regress xenophobia on the importance of religion and frequency of religious service attendance; does the importance of religion have a curve-shaped relationship with xenophobia? Make sure to not use orthogonal polynomials for this question. 
ols1 <- lm_robust(imwbcnt ~ poly(rlgdgr, 2, raw = TRUE) + rlgatnd, w = pspwght, data = ESS)
screenreg(ols1, include.ci = FALSE)
# 
# =========================================
#                               Model 1    
# -----------------------------------------
# (Intercept)                      4.25 ***
#                                 (0.05)   
# poly(rlgdgr, 2, raw = TRUE)1     0.12 ** 
#                                 (0.04)   
# poly(rlgdgr, 2, raw = TRUE)2    -0.01    
#                                 (0.01)   
# rlgatnd                         -0.09 *  
#                                 (0.05)   
# -----------------------------------------
# R^2                              0.00    
# Adj. R^2                         0.00    
# Num. obs.                     5305       
# RMSE                             2.16    
# =========================================
# *** p < 0.001; ** p < 0.01; * p < 0.05
  1. Model 3: Add cntry, eduyrs, par_edu, agea, and gndr as control variables, what happens to our curv-linear religiosity estimates? 
ols2 <- lm_robust(imwbcnt ~ poly(rlgdgr, 2, raw = TRUE) + rlgatnd + eduyrs + par_edu + cntry + gndr, w = pspwght, data = ESS)
screenreg(ols2, include.ci = FALSE)
# 
# =========================================
#                               Model 1    
# -----------------------------------------
# (Intercept)                      7.10 ***
#                                 (0.17)   
# poly(rlgdgr, 2, raw = TRUE)1     0.03    
#                                 (0.04)   
# poly(rlgdgr, 2, raw = TRUE)2    -0.00    
#                                 (0.01)   
# rlgatnd                         -0.07    
#                                 (0.05)   
# eduyrs                          -0.11 ***
#                                 (0.01)   
# par_edu                         -0.19 ***
#                                 (0.02)   
# cntryDenmark                    -0.46 ***
#                                 (0.09)   
# cntryNorway                     -0.57 ***
#                                 (0.09)   
# cntrySweden                     -1.24 ***
#                                 (0.10)   
# gndrFemale                      -0.24 ***
#                                 (0.07)   
# -----------------------------------------
# R^2                              0.10    
# Adj. R^2                         0.10    
# Num. obs.                     5305       
# RMSE                             2.06

# *** p < 0.001; ** p < 0.01; * p < 0.05
  1. Visualize the (not really curve-linear) relationship (i.e., visualize the predictions from your model.).
# Generate synthetic data to 
# visualize parental education
synth_data <- ESS %>%
   # Generate theoretically-informative 
   # but artificial tibble for predictions.
   data_grid(par_edu, gndr, cntry, rlgdgr, rlgatnd) %>%
   mutate( # Set confounders constant at their mean,
     eduyrs = mean(ESS$eduyrs, na.rm = TRUE),
     par_edu = mean(ESS$par_edu, na.rm = TRUE),
     rlgatnd = mean(ESS$rlgatnd, na.rm = TRUE),
     gndr = "Female",
     cntry = "Denmark") %>% # then
   unique() # Drop duplicates.

# Generate predictions and 95% confidence intervals, then
synth_data <- predict(ols2, newdata = synth_data,
                      interval = "confidence",
                      level = 0.95)$fit %>%
  as_tibble() %>% # Turn into a tibble, then
  bind_cols(synth_data, .) # Add to the synthetic data.


ggplot(data = synth_data, aes(y = fit, x = rlgdgr)) +
  geom_ribbon(aes(ymin = lwr, ymax = upr), alpha = 0.5) +
  geom_line() +
  labs(x = "Importance of religion",
  y = "Xenophobia",
  caption = "(Covariates set to: German women at mean levels of (parental) education)") + 
  theme_minimal()

  1. Is the relation between parental education and xenophobia conditional on the country of residence? Z-standardize parental education using I(). 
ols3 <- lm_robust(imwbcnt ~ poly(rlgdgr, 2, raw = TRUE) + rlgatnd + eduyrs + I(scale(par_edu))*cntry + gndr, w = pspwght, data = ESS)
screenreg(ols3, include.ci = FALSE)
# 
# =========================================
#                               Model 1    
# -----------------------------------------
# (Intercept)                      6.47 ***
#                                 (0.17)   
# poly(rlgdgr, 2, raw = TRUE)1     0.03    
#                                 (0.04)   
# poly(rlgdgr, 2, raw = TRUE)2    -0.00    
#                                 (0.01)   
# rlgatnd                         -0.07    
#                                 (0.05)   
# eduyrs                          -0.11 ***

#                                 (0.07)   
# cntryDenmark                    -0.47 ***
#                                 (0.09)   
# cntryNorway                     -0.58 ***
#                                 (0.09)   
# cntrySweden                     -1.25 ***

  1. Visualize the interaction effect.
# Generate synthetic data to 
# visualize parental education
synth_data <- ESS %>%
   # Generate theoretically-informative 
   # but artificial tibble for predictions.
   data_grid(par_edu, gndr, cntry, rlgdgr, rlgatnd) %>%
   mutate( # Set confounders constant at their mean,
     rlgdgr = mean(ESS$rlgdgr, na.rm = TRUE),
     rlgatnd = mean(ESS$rlgatnd, na.rm = TRUE),
     eduyrs = mean(ESS$eduyrs, na.rm = TRUE),
     gndr = "Female") %>% # then
   unique() # Drop duplicates.

# Generate predictions and 95% confidence intervals, then
synth_data <- predict(ols3, newdata = synth_data,
                      interval = "confidence",
                      level = 0.95)$fit %>%
  as_tibble() %>% # Turn into a tibble, then
  bind_cols(synth_data, .) # Add to the synthetic data.


ggplot(data = synth_data, aes(y = fit, x = par_edu)) +
  geom_ribbon(aes(ymin = lwr, ymax = upr, fill = cntry), alpha = 0.5) +
  geom_line(aes(color = cntry)) +
  labs(x = "Parental education",
       y = "Xenophobia",
       caption = "(Covariates set to: Women at mean levels of education, religiosity, and religious service attendance)",
       color = "Country", fill = "Country") + 
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(legend.position = c(0.87, 0.8),
        legend.background = 
          element_rect(fill = NA,
                       color = NA))
